<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8 species; length 17-26 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Bates" authorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Mecopelidnota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mecopelidnota" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mecopelidnota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinctive for their dark metallic green coloration, large size, elongate body form, and emargination at the base of the metatibia in the male. As currently constituted, the genus includes eight species (
<bibRefCitation author="Soula, M" journalOrPublisher="AECFT, Saintry" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B359" refString="Soula, M, 2008. Les Coleopteres du Nouveau Monde. Volume 2: Rutelini 2. Revision des Pelidnotina 2. Revision des genres: Parhoplognathus, Chipita n. gen., Heteropelidnota, Homothermon, Hoplopelidnota, Mesomerodon, Mecopelidnota, Patatra n. gen. (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae, Rutelinae, Rutelini). Besoiro: Supplement au Bulletin de liaison de l'Association Entomologique pour la Connaissance de la Faune Tropicale. AECFT, Saintry" title="Les Coleopteres du Nouveau Monde. Volume 2: Rutelini 2. Revision des Pelidnotina 2. Revision des genres: Parhoplognathus, Chipita n. gen., Heteropelidnota, Homothermon, Hoplopelidnota, Mesomerodon, Mecopelidnota, Patatra n. gen. (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae, Rutelinae, Rutelini). Besoiro: Supplement au Bulletin de liaison de l'Association Entomologique pour la Connaissance de la Faune Tropicale." year="2008">Soula 2008</bibRefCitation>
), but this may be an over-estimate. Members are distributed both on the east and west sides of the Andes in Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru. The record for 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. cylindrica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cylindrica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. cylindrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Guatemala is questionable (
<bibRefCitation author="Monzon, J" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Mundi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B220" refString="Monzon, J, 1996. Guia para los escarabajos (Coleoptera: Scarabaeoidea) de Guatemala. Universidad del Valle de Guatemala, Guatemala City." title="Guia para los escarabajos (Coleoptera: Scarabaeoidea) de Guatemala. Universidad del Valle de Guatemala, Guatemala City." year="1996">
<normalizedToken originalValue="MonzÃ³n">Monzon</normalizedToken>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The form of the male metatibia (base with an emargination) serves as a synapomorph for the group. Based on our analyses of external morphological characters, the genus includes two lineages: one to the west side of the Andes and one on the east of the Andes. Species on the west of the Andes (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. arrowi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="arrowi">M. arrowi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. cylindrica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cylindrica">M. cylindrica</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(Waterhouse), 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. marxi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="marxi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. marxi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Soula, and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. obscura" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[Taschenberg]) share the form of the male parameres (with enlarged 
<normalizedToken originalValue="âthumbâ">&quot;thumb&quot;</normalizedToken>
in lateral view) and greatly enlarged female gonocoxites. Species on the east side of the Andes (
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. witti" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="witti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. witti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ohaus, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. gerardi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="gerardi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. gerardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Soula, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. mezai" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="mezai">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. mezai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Soula, and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. dewynteri" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="dewynteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. dewynteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Soula) share the form of the male parameres (lacking the enlarged 
<normalizedToken originalValue="âthumbâ">&quot;thumb&quot;</normalizedToken>
in lateral view) and reduced female gonocoxites. Both lineages exhibit north-south clinal variation in the form of the male parameres, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Soula, M" journalOrPublisher="AECFT, Saintry" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B359" refString="Soula, M, 2008. Les Coleopteres du Nouveau Monde. Volume 2: Rutelini 2. Revision des Pelidnotina 2. Revision des genres: Parhoplognathus, Chipita n. gen., Heteropelidnota, Homothermon, Hoplopelidnota, Mesomerodon, Mecopelidnota, Patatra n. gen. (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae, Rutelinae, Rutelini). Besoiro: Supplement au Bulletin de liaison de l'Association Entomologique pour la Connaissance de la Faune Tropicale. AECFT, Saintry" title="Les Coleopteres du Nouveau Monde. Volume 2: Rutelini 2. Revision des Pelidnotina 2. Revision des genres: Parhoplognathus, Chipita n. gen., Heteropelidnota, Homothermon, Hoplopelidnota, Mesomerodon, Mecopelidnota, Patatra n. gen. (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae, Rutelinae, Rutelini). Besoiro: Supplement au Bulletin de liaison de l'Association Entomologique pour la Connaissance de la Faune Tropicale." year="2008">Soula (2008</bibRefCitation>
: 23) also alludes to this 
<normalizedToken originalValue="âtransitionalâ">&quot;transitional&quot;</normalizedToken>
variation in species on either side of the Andes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Species in the genus are recorded from less than 10 m elevation (
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. cylindrica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cylindrica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. cylindrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. obscura" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Paucar-Cabrera, A" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 92" refId="B304" refString="Paucar-Cabrera, A, 2005. A catalog and distributional analysis of the Rutelinae (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae) of Ecuador. Zootaxa 948: 1 - 92" title="A catalog and distributional analysis of the Rutelinae (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae) of Ecuador." volume="948" year="2005">Paucar-Cabrera 2005</bibRefCitation>
) to 2700 m (
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. obscura" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Ohaus, F" journalOrPublisher="Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="383 - 408" refId="B268" refString="Ohaus, F, 1908b. Die Ruteliden meiner Sammelreisen in Suedamerika (Col.). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 1908: 383 - 408" title="Die Ruteliden meiner Sammelreisen in Suedamerika (Col.)." volume="1908" year="1908 b">Ohaus (1908b)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. arrowi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="arrowi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. arrowi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the flowers of yellow 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Mimosa" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mimosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Leguminosae</taxonomicName>
) in Guayaquil, Ecuador, during the rainy season. In Ecuador, species were collected January to April in tropical regions (
<bibRefCitation author="Paucar-Cabrera, A" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 92" refId="B304" refString="Paucar-Cabrera, A, 2005. A catalog and distributional analysis of the Rutelinae (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae) of Ecuador. Zootaxa 948: 1 - 92" title="A catalog and distributional analysis of the Rutelinae (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae) of Ecuador." volume="948" year="2005">Paucar-Cabrera 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae and sister-group relationships are not known.
</paragraph>
